s a whole, emphasizing Yourcenar’s profound knowledge of the ancient evidence on which her life of Hadrian is based and exploiting a wide range of contemporary Yourcenarian criticism. The book pays special attention to the methods by which Yourcenar believed Hadrian’s life history to be recoverable, compares examples of modern life-writing, and contrasts the procedures of conventional Roman biographers. Revealing how and why Mémoires d’Hadrien is as it is, Marguerite Yourcenar’s Hadrian illustrates how imaginative literary recreation is often little different from historical speculation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBiography as a literary form. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aClassics.  aFrench literature.  aMarguerite Yourcenar.  aMémoires d’Hadrien.  aRoman emperor Hadrian.  aRoman imperial biography.  aancient Rome.  aancient history.  ahistorical novels.  anovels set in ancient Rome.1 aBrown, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGellhorn, Martha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGibbon, Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLambert, Royston, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMomigliano, A.D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSyme, Ronald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWoolf, Virginia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWordsworth, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYourcenar, Marguerite, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079737440uhttps: